# Patches (`patches/`) — rules & sync workflow

> Source canonique : `.agents/patches.md`

This file governs the local forks under `patches/` (`adabraka-gpui`,
`adabraka-ui`, …). It is the source of truth for both:

- **Conventions**: how our local modifications are marked, tracked, and
  documented so they don't get lost when we lift a fork to a newer
  upstream version.
- **Workflow**: how the `/sync-patches` slash command lifts a fork to a
  newer upstream release without losing any of our changes.

## Why we vendor

Some upstream bugs / missing features block us today and can't wait for a
crates.io release. The alternatives (git-dep fork on GitHub, upstream
PRs, cargo-patch, live workarounds) were considered — the current call is
a local vendor because `patches/adabraka-gpui` was already following
that pattern at repo genesis. If a fork's diff grows past ~50 hunks or
we need to sync more than every few weeks, revisit that call — a
GitHub-fork + `[patch.crates-io] { git = "…", rev = "…" }` is usually
lighter long-term.

## Marker convention

Every local change inside `patches/<crate>/src/` must be introduced by a
comment that starts with `// ShellDeck patch:` (or `/// ShellDeck patch:`
for doc comments). The marker must sit **immediately before** the code
it justifies — no orphan markers, no batched multi-file markers.

Example:

```rust
// ShellDeck patch: the upstream `set_value` was a no-op when the
// selection was empty; select the whole content first so replace
// actually overwrites.
self.selected_range = 0..self.content.len();
self.replace_text_in_range(None, &filtered_value, window, cx);
```

Two hard rules on markers:

1. **No marker, no replay.** The `/sync-patches` audit greps for these
   markers and matches them against the `Markers` list of every
   `PATCHES.md` entry. A marker in code with no entry — or an entry
   with no marker in code — halts the sync.
2. **One block, one marker; one SDPATCH may span several markers.** A
   single edit gets one marker (not one per line), but a single logical
   fix that legitimately spans multiple non-adjacent locations (e.g. a
   struct field + the two call sites that consume it) gets one marker
   per site and lists them all in the SDPATCH entry. Do not consolidate
   these into a single misleading marker.

## `PATCHES.md` inventory (one per fork)

Every vendored fork has a `patches/<crate>/PATCHES.md` at its root. It
is the machine-readable ledger of what we changed and why. Schema:

```markdown
# Patches — <crate>

**Vendored from**: `<crate>` v<X.Y.Z>
**Upstream**: https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>
**Last synced**: <YYYY-MM-DD>

## Patches

### SDPATCH-001 — <short title>

- **Files / symbols**:
  - `src/path/to/file.rs` — `Type::method`
  - `src/other/file.rs` — `mod::function` *(only when the fix legitimately
    spans multiple locations)*
- **Markers** (one line per marker in code — the audit matches by count):
  - `src/path/to/file.rs:123` — `// ShellDeck patch: <first line>`
  - `src/other/file.rs:45` — `// ShellDeck patch: <first line>`
- **Why**: <one paragraph, focus on the *why* not the *what* — the code
  already shows the what>
- **Upstream status**: <open PR link / issue link / "not filed yet">

### SDPATCH-002 — …

## Sync log

- **YYYY-MM-DD** — from vX.Y.Z to vA.B.C. SDPATCH-003 needed adaptation
  (upstream renamed `foo` to `bar`). All others replayed clean.
```

Rules:

- **IDs are sticky.** Once a patch has `SDPATCH-007`, it keeps that ID
  even after we drop or rewrite it. Reusing IDs corrupts the sync log.
- **When upstream ships the fix** (e.g. our `set_value("")` PR gets
  merged), the entry stays in `PATCHES.md` under a `## Retired
  patches` section with the sync date it was removed — future me
  wants to know why the diff shrank.

## `/sync-patches` — the workflow

Input parsing (see `.claude/commands/sync-patches.md` for the entry
point):

- No args → list the forks that have a `PATCHES.md`, print the pinned
  version of each, and ask what to sync.
- `all` → run the workflow sequentially across every fork; stop on
  first red patch.
- `<crate>` → sync that crate to the latest release available (crates.io
  or the GitHub repo, whichever ships a newer tag).
- `<crate> <version>` → sync that crate to that exact tag.

The workflow is single-fork, run one at a time (even under `all`):

1. **Pre-flight**. Working tree clean, or the user explicitly opts in to
   dirty. `patches/<crate>/PATCHES.md` exists. Marker count in code
   matches inventory count. Cargo lockfile is committed.
2. **Snapshot**. `git switch -c sync-patches/<crate>-<from>-to-<to>`.
   Do **not** delete this branch at the end.
3. **Fetch upstream**. Prefer the GitHub tag tarball (crates.io strips
   assets we may rely on):
   `curl -sSL https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>/archive/refs/tags/v<ver>.tar.gz`
   into `/tmp/sync-<crate>-<ver>/`.
4. **Vanilla reference**. Also fetch the currently-pinned version into
   `/tmp/sync-<crate>-vanilla/`. This is the "before our patches"
   baseline needed to compute our diff precisely.
5. **Overlay**. Copy the new upstream tree over `patches/<crate>/`,
   preserving `PATCHES.md`, top-level metadata files we intentionally
   edit (e.g. `Cargo.toml` if we tweak features), and any files listed
   under `## Preserved files` in `PATCHES.md`.
6. **Replay patches**. Walk `PATCHES.md` in ascending SDPATCH-NNN
   order. For each entry, apply the patch — via `git apply`, `patch
   -p1`, or a direct edit if the fix is small. **One SDPATCH = one
   commit.** Never batch.
7. **Marker audit**. `grep -rn "ShellDeck patch:" patches/<crate>/src/`
   total count must equal the sum of the `Markers` lists across every
   `PATCHES.md` entry (not the entry count — an SDPATCH may declare
   several markers). Every line listed in `PATCHES.md` must resolve to
   a matching marker in code; every marker in code must map to an
   entry. Missing markers are always a bug in the replay — restore,
   don't silently drop.
8. **Compile check**.
   `PKG_CONFIG_PATH=/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/pkgconfig cargo check`.
   Fix mechanical breakage (renames, moved modules, changed
   signatures) inline. If a fix needs design judgement, **stop** and
   report.
9. **Regression sweep**. `cargo test --workspace`. Any newly-red test
   is a report item, not silent triage.
10. **Update inventory**. Bump `Vendored from` + `Last synced` in
    `PATCHES.md`. Add a `## Sync log` line noting which patches
    replayed clean, which needed adaptation, and which upstream now
    ships natively (candidates for retirement).
11. **Report**. In the final message to the user:
    - New version pinned.
    - Per-patch status: green / yellow (adapted, with the exact edit)
      / red (couldn't replay, with the reason).
    - Upstream additions that supersede one of our patches — flag as
      candidates for retirement.
    - The safety branch name so they can inspect / roll back.

## Non-negotiables

- **Never** merge a sync that has unresolved red patches. Hand the
  report back to the user.
- **Never** touch `patches/adabraka-gpui/src/elements/div.rs` unless the
  user explicitly names it. That file hosts the smooth-scroll animation
  WIP owned by Benjamin Favre and it is *not* part of the replayable
  patch set (no marker convention applies).
- **Never** creatively refactor upstream code to make our patches fit.
  If cargo check still fails after two mechanical fix rounds, stop and
  produce a report.
- **Never** delete the safety branch created in step 2. The user needs
  it if the report surfaces something they want to unwind.

## Bootstrap mode

If `/sync-patches <crate>` is called on a fork that has no
`PATCHES.md`:

1. Download the vanilla source of the currently-pinned version to
   `/tmp/sync-<crate>-vanilla/`.
2. `diff -ru` against `patches/<crate>/` — every non-metadata hunk is a
   candidate patch.
3. Draft a `PATCHES.md` with one `SDPATCH-NNN` per logical hunk. For
   each, propose a title, the touched file/symbol, the marker line
   (verbatim if it exists, otherwise flag as *unmarked* — the user must
   add the marker before the first real sync).
4. **Ask the user to review before writing anything to disk.**
   Bootstrap is a mapping exercise — silent inventories are worse than
   no inventory.

